0":"omkring 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England",", , , England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1360–":"circa 1360–Overleden","1360–1380":"1360–1380","1380–Male":"1380–Overleden","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","Abt 1360":"circa 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1360–":"about 1360–Deceased","1360–1380":"1360–1380","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","Abt 1360":"about 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England",", , , England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southeast), Dutch, and Czech: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’ (see   Hermann  ). In England this name was introduced by the Normans.","Irish: variant of   Hargadon  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): perhaps a nickname for someone with a copious or noticeable head of hair (see   Haar  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hargadon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","Irish (Sligo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArgadáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Argadán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>argad</i> ‘silver’. In Galway the traditional form <i>O'Hargadan</i> has tended to be replaced by <i>Hardeman</i>, and elsewhere in Ireland by   Harman   and   Harmon  ."]},{"name":"Herman","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Dutch, Flemish, Hungarian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Harman   5.","Americanized form of German   Hermann  , a cognate of 1 above.","English: perhaps a shortened form of <b>Herniman</b>, a topographic name for a ‘dweller (in a) nook or corner of land’, from Middle English <i>herne</i>, <i>hirne</i>, <i>hurne</i> + <i>man</i>. See also   Hearn  ."]},{"name":"Hermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Harman was born about 1360, in Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Walter Harman or Harmon. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1360–1380":"1360–1380","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1360–":"noin 1360–Kuollut","1360–1380":"1360–1380","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","Abt 1360":"noin 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1360–":"environ 1360–Décédé","1360–1380":"1360–1380","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","Abt 1360":"environ 1360","1455":"1455","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, Angleterre",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Walter Harman est né environ 1360, à Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs Walter Harman or Harmon. Il est décédé à Angl